Upon inspecting the unique values above, I notice a few columns have only 1 unique value, and license is not boolean.¶

I have updated the conversions needed and data groupings sections to reflect this information.¶

Requires license should be dropped in favor of license NaN values. That 'CITY TAX' value should be looked into as well.¶

The conversions are performed below:¶

In [13]:
# boolean conversions
for col in df[['host_is_superhost',
               'host_has_profile_pic',
               'host_identity_verified',
               'is_location_exact',
               'has_availability',
               'requires_license',
#                'license',
               'require_guest_profile_picture',
               'require_guest_phone_verification',
               'instant_bookable',
               'is_business_travel_ready']]:
    if len(df[col].unique()) != 1:
        df.loc[df[col]=='t',col] = True
        df.loc[df[col]=='f',col] = False
    else:
        del df[col]

Commas, dollar signs, and percentages¶

In [22]:
def update_relative_calendar_values(value):
    # included years even though it is not included in the calendar values
    # future proofing attempt
    if value == 'today':
        return today
    elif value == 'never':
        return np.NaN
    elif value == 'yesterday':
        return today + relativedelta(days=-1)
    elif value == 'a month ago':
        return today + relativedelta(months=-1)
    elif value == 'a week ago':
        return today + relativedelta(weeks=-1)
    elif value == 'a year ago':
        return today + relativedelta(years=-1)
    else:
        to_be_subtracted = pd.to_numeric(int(value.split(" ")[0]))
        if 'days' in value:
            return today + relativedelta(days=-to_be_subtracted)
        elif 'week' in value:
            return today + relativedelta(weeks=-to_be_subtracted)
        elif 'month' in value:
            return today + relativedelta(months=-to_be_subtracted)
        elif 'year' in value:
            return today + relativedelta(years=-to_be_subtracted)
In [23]:

It's very interesting that 50% of the availability data is at 0 calendar days available. Likely means it's not a good feature to predict price.¶

That's highly skewed. Even with a log transform.

In [68]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = np.array(df['bedrooms']).reshape(-1,1)
y = np.array(df['price']).reshape(-1,1)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=0)

reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_train,y_train)
y_pred = reg.predict(X_test)

print("R^2 Value:\n",reg.score(X,y))
print("\nSlope:\n",reg.coef_[0])
print("\nMean Squared Error:\n",mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred))
print("\nY-intercept:\n",reg.intercept_)
print("\n",df.groupby('bedrooms').price.describe()[['mean','std']])

Comparing the regression models for bedrooms vs. beds, we see a lower R2, lower Slope, higher Error value, and higher y-intercept.¶

What can we conclude from this comparison?

  1. The number of rooms drives the price more than the number of beds.
  2. The number of beds, alone, is not a good predictor of price.
  3. At 0 beds in a listing, this model predicts a price of $107.

The next cell will measure the number of outliers in numeric columns. If there are less outliers in the log transformed column than the original data, I will apply a log transform onto the column.¶

There are a few reasons to do this:

  1. Log transformation could reduce the influence of outliers.
  2. It can eliminate heteroscedasticity which means the variance of variable X increases as the X value increases. Heteroscedasticity can confound confidence intervals and hypotheses tests.
  3. You can make your variable more normalized, though this is not a good reason.
In [74]:
for col in df.select_dtypes(['int64','int','float']).drop(["latitude","longitude","host_id","id","scrape_id"],axis=1):
    
    outliers = np.where(
        np.abs(
            stats.zscore(
                df[col]
            )
        ) > 3 )[0]
    
    log_transformed_outliers = np.where(
        np.abs(
            stats.zscore(
                df[col].apply(
                    lambda x: np.log(x) if (x != 0) & (x != np.nan) else 1e-100
                )
            )
        ) > 3 )[0]
    
    print(df[col].name)
    print("outliers:",len(outliers))
    print("log transformed outliers:",len(log_transformed_outliers))
    print()
    if (len(log_transformed_outliers) < len(outliers)) & ("review_scores" not in col):
        df[col] = df[col].apply(lambda x: np.log(x) if (x != 0) & (x != np.nan) else 1e-20)

Now I want to view if I have any normal variables.¶

The Jarque-Bera test estimates the likelihood that the underlying variable is normal with 95% confidence. Our null hypothesis, or H0, is the underlying variable is not normally distributed. If the P-value is over 0.05, we can reject our null hypothesis and assume the variable IS normally distributed.

In [75]:
from statsmodels.stats.stattools import jarque_bera

for col in df.select_dtypes(['int64','int','float']).drop(["latitude","longitude","host_id","id","scrape_id"],axis=1):
    
    test_stat, pval, skew, kurt = jarque_bera(df[col])
    
    print(df[col].name,
          "\nSkewness (normal=0):",
          skew,
          "\nKurtosis (normal=0):",
          kurt-3,    # normal curve has a kurtosis of 3 by default 
          "\nP-value:",
          pval,
          "\nJarque-Bera Test Statistic:",
          test_stat,
          "\n")

Now I'm interested to see where these listings are located. Let's perform a K-means algorithm on the Latitude and Longitude, then plot the clusters on a map.¶

In [76]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist, pdist

Y_axis = np.array(df['latitude']).reshape(-1,1)
X_axis = np.array(df['longitude']).reshape(-1,1)

K_clusters = range(1,10)
kmeans = [KMeans(n_clusters=i).fit(Y_axis) for i in K_clusters]

centroids = [k.cluster_centers_ for k in kmeans]

Distance_k = [cdist(Y_axis, centroid, 'euclidean') for centroid in centroids]
dist = [np.min(D, axis=1) for D in Distance_k]

wcss = [sum(d**2) for d in dist]
total_sum_square = sum(pdist(Y_axis)**2)/Y_axis.shape[0]
bss = total_sum_square - wcss

# score = [kmeans[i].fit(Y_axis) for i in range(len(kmeans))]

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))
# ax.scatter(x=df['latitude'],y=df['longitude'])
ax.plot(K_clusters, bss/total_sum_square*100)
ax.set_title("Elbow Curve")
ax.set_xlabel("Clusters")
ax.set_ylabel("Percentage of variance explained")
plt.show()

The Percentage of Variance Explained heuristic tapers off at 5 clusters. Let's choose that number of means.

Using the K-nearest Neighbors classifier, I am going to infer and impute the neighbourhood, street, zipcode, market, and city columns by the nearest neighbor.¶

In [82]:
from sklearn import neighbors
knn = neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(1,weights='uniform')

for col in df[['neighbourhood',
               'neighbourhood_cleansed',
               'street',
               'zipcode',
               'market',
               'city']].columns:
    if len(df.loc[df[col].isna()])!=0: #some columns have all their values
        knn.fit(df.loc[~df[col].isna(),['latitude','longitude']], #training variables
                df.loc[~df[col].isna(),col])                      #target variable
        df.loc[df[col].isna(),col] = knn.predict(df.loc[df[col].isna(),['latitude','longitude']])
        print("Null values left:",df[col].name,len(df.loc[df[col].isna()]))

In [83]:
def encode_and_bind(original_dataframe, feature_to_encode):
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(original_dataframe[[feature_to_encode]])
    res = pd.concat([original_dataframe, dummies], axis=1)
    res = res.drop([feature_to_encode], axis=1)
    return(res)

import nltk
from nltk.sentiment.vader import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer

sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

def sentiment_calc(text):
    try:
        return sid.polarity_scores(text)
    except:
        pass

This next cell will take a long time to process. I'm going to use the polarity scores in PCA decomposition. I'm going to start making my model pipeline.

def model_fit(alg,dtrain,target):
    xgb_param = alg.get_xgb_params()
    xgtrain = xgb.DMatrix(dtrain.values,label=target)
    cvresult = xgb.cv(xgb_param,
                      xgtrain,
                      num_boost_round=alg.get_params()['n_estimators'],
                      nfold=5,
                      early_stopping_rounds=50)
    
    #alg.fit(dtrain,target,use_best_model=True,eval_set=(x_val,y_val))
    alg.fit(dtrain,target)
    print("Model Report")
    print("Accuracy is {}".format(alg.score(val_X,val_y)))
    print("Number of Features:",len(dtrain.columns))
    
    feat_imp = pd.Series(alg.feature_importances_,dtrain.columns).sort_values(ascending=False)
    feat_imp[:20].plot(kind='bar', title='Feature Importances')
    plt.ylabel('Feature Importance Score')

As you can see, the number of people the rental property can accomodate, followed by the type of room type and by the number of bathrooms and bedrooms, were the most important features for predicting the daily price.

My XGBoost Regressor consistently achieves an R2 correlation coefficient of 65%. Based on my 5-fold cross-validation scores, my model performs nearly as well on out of sample data.¶

  1. My background is rooted in Economics and Finance making me particularly adept with Time Series Analysis.
  2. All of these techniques I learned on my own, imagine what I will be able to do with proper resources and training.
  3. I am self-motivated and enjoy the process of testing my hypotheses and experimentation.
  4. I have experience using many technologies for visualizations, web development, and marketing analytics.

Some things I think I did well:¶

  • Used most of the original data
  • Use log transforms to handle outliers
  • Separated the amenities and host_verification columns into multiple boolean columns
  • Prevented information loss by encoding many dummy variables
  • Used sentiment analysis on descriptive columns
  • Used KNearestNeighbors to impute location data
  • Utilized multiple different models to get a sense for which worked best.
    • Boosting worked the best because it combines weaker features into stronger features. Based on the separation of the amenities and host_verification columns, this technique provided the best results.
